      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Understanding the IELTS Test Format</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The International English Language Testing System (IELTS) measures your ability to communicate in English across four modules: Listening, Reading, Writing, and Speaking. The test is accepted by over 11,000 organizations worldwide including universities, employers, and immigration authorities.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">There are two versions: IELTS Academic for those applying to higher education, and IELTS General Training for work or immigration purposes. Both versions test the same four modules, though the Reading and Writing prompts differ in subject matter.</p>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-emerald-600 mb-2">Listening</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">40 questions · 30 minutes</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Four recorded monologues and conversations</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-4">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-emerald-600 mb-2">Reading</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">40 questions · 60 minutes</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Three long passages with questions</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-4">
