        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Your IELTS Preparation Timeline</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Effective IELTS preparation requires structured study over time. Rushing through materials rarely produces the band scores needed for your goals. Here is a recommended timeline based on your starting level:</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Weeks 1-2: Baseline Assessment</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Take a full practice IELTS test under timed conditions to establish your current band score. Focus on identifying which modules are your weakest. Pay particular attention to the Writing and Speaking sections where self-assessment is most difficult. Consider booking a diagnostic session with an <a href="/reviews/italki/" class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">iTalki tutor</a> or See Guru coach for expert feedback.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Weeks 3-6: Focused Skill Building</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Dedicate each week to specific skills within each module. In Listening, practice with diverse accents (British, Australian, American, Canadian). For Reading, build your vocabulary around academic and general topics. Writing requires studying model essays and understanding examiner marking criteria. Speaking needs regular conversation practice with native or fluent speakers.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">This phase is where <a href="/reviews/italki/" class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">1-on-1 tutoring</a> delivers the highest value. A qualified IELTS tutor can identify your specific weak points and provide targeted correction.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Weeks 7-10: Intensive Practice</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Take full practice tests every 3-4 days. Review every answer you get wrong and understand why. Build your writing speed so you can complete both tasks with time to spare. Practice Speaking with recorded mock tests to reduce anxiety. Consider joining a structured course for access to official practice materials.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Weeks 11-12: Test Readiness</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">In the final two weeks, focus on maintaining your skills through light practice. Avoid learning new material that might confuse you. Get plenty of rest before the test. Ensure you have your test day materials ready. If you are booking a test soon, consider an intensive final session with your tutor to polish your approach.</p>

      <AdUnit />

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">IELTS Preparation Strategies by Module</h2>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Listening Preparation</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The IELTS Listening test plays recorded audio once. You write answers while listening and have 10 minutes to transfer them to the answer sheet at the end. Key strategies include reading questions before the audio plays, anticipating the type of answer needed (name, number, date), and practicing with diverse English accents.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Common pitfalls include misspelling answers and running out of time to transfer responses. Practice transferring answers cleanly and double-check your spelling of names and technical terms.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Reading Preparation</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The IELTS Reading test requires reading three long passages and answering 40 questions in 60 minutes. There is no time to read every word. Skimming for main ideas and scanning for specific details are essential skills. Learn to identify question types (True/False/Not Given, Multiple Choice, Matching, Summary completion) and their specific strategies.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Vocabulary building is crucial. Focus on academic words commonly tested in IELTS Reading. Resources like <a href="/resources/free-online-english-courses/" class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">free online English courses</a> can help build the vocabulary foundation you need.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Writing Preparation</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Task 1 requires describing visual information (graph, chart, diagram) in at least 150 words. Task 2 is an essay responding to an argument or problem in at least 250 words. Task 2 carries more weight and should receive more attention.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The four marking criteria are Task Achievement, Coherence and Cohesion, Lexical Resource, and Grammatical Range and Accuracy. Each is worth 25% of your score. You need structured feedback to improve on these criteria. Self-study alone cannot identify patterns in your writing that hold your score back.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Work with an <a href="/reviews/italki/" class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">IELTS tutor on iTalki</a> or See Guru to submit writing tasks for detailed feedback on all four criteria.</p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Speaking Preparation</h3>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The Speaking test has three parts: a warm-up interview (4-5 minutes), a 1-2 minute short speech on a topic you receive on a card (2 minutes to prepare), and a two-way discussion (4-5 minutes). The examiner scores Fluency and Coherence, Lexical Resource, Grammatical Range and Accuracy, and Pronunciation.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Practice speaking on diverse topics. Prepare ideas for common Part 2 themes (people, places, experiences, objects, activities). Record yourself speaking and listen back for filler words ("um," "uh," "like"), hesitation patterns, and pronunciation issues.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Nothing replaces real conversation practice. See Guru offers unlimited speaking sessions with tutors who specialize in IELTS preparation, giving you the real-time feedback you need to improve your fluency and confidence.</p>

