      <div class="space-y-6 mb-10">
        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">How long does IELTS preparation take?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">Most learners need 2-3 months of dedicated IELTS preparation to move up half a band score. If you are starting at Band 5.5 and need Band 7.0, plan for at least 8-12 weeks of consistent study. Those needing to move from Band 6.0 to 7.5 typically require 12-16 weeks. The exact timeline depends on your current level, target score, and how much time you can commit daily.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">What is the hardest part of IELTS to prepare for?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">Writing Task 2 and the Speaking module are generally the hardest to improve without expert guidance. Writing requires mastering specific essay structures, argument development, and examiner criteria that are difficult to self-assess. Speaking needs real-time interaction with native speakers who can give honest feedback on pronunciation, fluency, and vocabulary range. Both benefit enormously from 1-on-1 tutoring.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">Is self-study enough for IELTS preparation?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">Self-study can work for Band 5.5-6.5 targets, especially for Reading and Listening which respond well to practice tests. However, self-study alone rarely pushes scores above Band 7.0 because you need expert feedback on Writing and Speaking. The best approach combines self-study materials with regular 1-on-1 sessions from a qualified IELTS tutor.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">Which IELTS modules should I focus on most?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">Focus most on the modules that are furthest from your target. If your Writing is consistently 1.0 band below your other scores, that should be your priority. Generally, Reading and Listening are easier to self-improve through practice tests. Writing and Speaking require more guided attention. Track your progress with practice tests every two weeks to identify which modules need the most work.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">How much do IELTS preparation tutors cost?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">IELTS tutors range from $5 per session with community tutors on See Guru to $80+ per hour for premium certified IELTS coaches. On iTalki, certified IELTS teachers typically charge $15-30 per hour. See Guru offers sessions starting from $5-12 with AI-matched tutors who specialize in IELTS modules. Investing in tutoring for Writing and Speaking is usually the highest-ROI preparation expense.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-900/40 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2">What are the best free IELTS preparation resources?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">The British Council offers free practice tests and preparation materials. IELTS Liz provides hundreds of free video lessons on YouTube. The official IELTS.org website has free sample papers and examiner videos. Cambridge also offers free practice materials. However, free resources cannot replace feedback on your writing and speaking from qualified instructors.</p>
        </div>
